The '''black-billed gull''' ('''''Chroicocephalus bulleri'''''), also called '''Buller's gull''' or {{lang|mi|tarāpuka}} ([[Māori language|Māori]]), is a [[Near Threatened]] species of [[gull]] in the family [[Laridae]].<ref name = NZBO>{{cite web |url=http://nzbirdsonline.org.nz/species/black-billed-gull |title=Black-billed gull |last1=McClellan |first1=R. K. |last2=Habraken |first2=A. |year=2017 |orig-date=2013 |website=New Zealand Birds Online |access-date=5 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190603005424/http://www.nzbirdsonline.org.nz/species/black-billed-gull |archive-date=3 June 2019 }}</ref><ref name = McBride2018>{{cite web |url=https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2018/01/31/just-a-seagull-nope/ |title=Just a Seagull? Nope |last=McBride |first=Abby |date=31 January 2018 |website=National Geographic Blog |access-date=7 January 2019 |archive-date=12 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230512041326/https://blog.nationalgeographic.org/2018/01/31/just-a-seagull-nope/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name = McBride2012>{{cite thesis |last=McBride |first=Abby |date=2012 |title=Don't Call It a Seagull! |type=Masters |publisher=MIT |url=https://cmsw.mit.edu/dont-call-seagull/ }}</ref> This gull is found only in [[New Zealand]], its ancestors having arrived from [[Australia]] around 250,000 years ago.<!--url for following ref may need updating in future, but note that this is a print magazine as well, so the url can be updated/removed without the ref being defunct--><ref name=Morris2019>{{cite magazine |last=Morris |first=Bill |date=January–February 2019 |title=Tending the Flock |url=https://www.nzgeo.com/stories/tending-the-flock/?source=homepage |magazine=New Zealand Geographic |volume=155 }}</ref>{{rp|89}}

==Taxonomy==
[[File:Bul02BirdP029.jpg|thumb|left|J. G. Keulemans's 1888 illustration of black-billed gull (front) with [[red-billed gull]] (''Chroicocephalus novaehollandiae scopulinus'')]]
Originally named ''Gavia pomare'' in 1855 by [[Carl Friedrich Bruch]], the name was rejected by the New Zealand ornithologist [[Walter Buller|Sir Walter Lawry Buller]] because it was already being used for another species.<ref name = Buller1888>{{cite book |last=Buller |first=Walter Lawry |date=1888 |title=A History of the Birds of New Zealand |url=http://mebooks.co.nz/a-history-of-the-birds-of-new-zealand-ebook |edition=2nd |location=London |access-date=7 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190107232950/http://mebooks.co.nz/a-history-of-the-birds-of-new-zealand-ebook |archive-date=7 January 2019 }}</ref>{{rp|58–59}} He then took up [[Prince Napoléon Bonaparte]]'s "playful" genus name ''Bruchigavia'' (literally, "Bruch's seabird")<ref>{{cite book |last=Jobling |first=James A. |date=2010 |title=Helm's Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names: From Aalge to Zusii |location=London |publisher=Christopher Helm |page=78 |isbn=978-1-4081-3326-2 }}</ref> as a provisional name for New Zealand gulls.<ref name = Buller1888 />{{rp|60}} But because Buller's proposed species name ''melanoryncha'' (literally, "black-billed")<ref name = Higgins1996>{{cite book |editor1-last=Higgins |editor1-first=P. J. |editor2-last=Davies |editor2-first=S. J. J. F. |date=1996 |title=Handbook of Australian, New Zealand & Antarctic Birds: Volume 3: Snipe to Pigeons |location=Melbourne, Australia |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=978-0-19-553070-4 }}</ref>{{rp|545}} had already been given to another gull species, [[Frederick Hutton (scientist)|Frederick Hutton]] suggested the name ''bulleri'', in honor of Buller, in 1871.<ref>{{cite book |last=Norman |first=Geoff |date=2018 |title=Birdstories: A History of the Birds of New Zealand |location=Nelson, New Zealand |publisher=Potton & Burton |page=170 |isbn=978-0-947503-92-5 }}</ref><ref name = Buller1888 />{{rp|59}} Buller accepted the offer and followed others in adopting the "larger and better-defined genus" of ''[[Larus]]''.<ref name = Buller1888 />{{rp|59}} The alternative common name '''Buller's gull''' also retains the connection to Buller.

The species is now considered to belong within the genus ''[[Chroicocephalus]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://avibase.bsc-eoc.org/species.jsp?lang=EN&avibaseid=1E12A4D6A917105F|title = Black-billed Gull: Chroicocephalus bulleri (Hutton, FW, 1871)|website= AviBase }}</ref><ref name = CoL /> The [[holotype]] is in the collection of the [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Black-billed Gull, Larus bulleri Hutton, 1871|url = http://collections.tepapa.govt.nz/object/613683|website = collections.tepapa.govt.nz|access-date = 21 June 2015|publisher = [[Museum of New Zealand Te Papa Tongarewa|Te Papa]]}}</ref>

==Description==
A healthy adult black-billed gull is typically 35–38&nbsp;cm long, with a wingspan of 81–96&nbsp;cm, and a weight of around 230g.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|545}} The head, body, and parts of the wings are white, with silvery grey on the saddle and wings, as well as black edging on the wings.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|546}} The gull also undergoes some seasonal color change. While typically black from February to June, the [[orbital ring]] is orange-red, red, or dark red the rest of the year.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|556}} The legs, too, change from black to dark red and even bright red as the breeding season progresses, "possibly stimulated by presence of begging chicks and juveniles."<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|556}} Observations suggest the gull is sexually dimorphic, but there is a lack of published data to support this.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|557}} There is likewise a lack of data in regard to geographical variation.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|557}}

Easily mistaken for the red-billed gull, the black-billed gull is distinguished by its black bill and is described as having a "more delicate appearance", a "more buoyant and graceful" flight, and being "generally less noisy", despite having a similar call.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|546}} [[F1 hybrid|F1]] and [[F1 hybrid#F2 hybrid|F2 hybrid]]s between the two gulls have been observed, both hybrids exhibiting dark red bills.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|556}}

==Behaviour==
Colonies are formed around the first pair that begins nesting. Where more than one pair forms the initial nest, clustering around these sites takes place within the colony. Colonies are frequently tightly packed, with "Gulls little more than pecking distance from each other and nests often touch, leaving little room for taking off and landing".<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|550}} Males may display aggressive behaviour towards others in an "ill-defined area"<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|550}} for a few minutes before leaving the area and forgetting it. Nonetheless, not all male aggression is linked to defending a particular area, and some pairs without chicks will show aggression towards those with chicks. Fights are rarely prolonged, usually consisting of a single attack by the aggressor, employing the bill for pecking, the wings for beating, and the legs for scratching. The target typically retreats right away. Adults [[Bird#Resting and roosting|roost]] at the breeding colony or feeding sites, though the latter is more common.<ref name = Higgins1996 />{{rp|551–52}}

Black-billed gulls can find themselves in conflict with humans. In 2024, black-billed gulls nesting in the "[[Christchurch Seagull Pit]]" near [[New Regent Street]] were deemed a "menace" by locals.<ref name=press-2024-menace/> They had been nesting in the flooded foundations of a demolished office block nearby, and had spread to nesting on nearby rooftops.<ref name=press-2024-menace/> The gulls were causing a nuisance by stealing food from tables and fouling the area.<ref name=press-2024-menace/> A local café owner said, "They shit everywhere. They're also not afraid of people any more. They'll swoop down and get food off your plate. They dive bomb. Small children don't stand a chance."<ref name=press-2024-menace>{{citation|title=Menace gulls turn tourist hot spot into 'eyesore'|language=en|work=[[The Press]] |url-access=subscription|first1=Tina|last1=Law|date=2024-11-10|access-date=2024-11-10|url=https://www.thepress.co.nz/nz-news/360479197/menace-gulls-turn-tourist-hot-spot-eyesore}}</ref> Due to their protected status, nothing could be done to remove the birds.<ref name=press-2024-menace/>

==Distribution and habitat==
[[File:Chroicocephalus bulleri.JPG|thumb|right|Adult at [[Lake Taupō]]]]
The black-billed gull is [[Endemism|endemic]] to New Zealand. Up to 78% of the total population is estimated to be living in the [[Southland Region|Southland]] region, on the southern end of the [[South Island]].<ref>{{Cite web|last= Hutching| first=Gerard| title = Red and black-billed gulls|url = http://www.teara.govt.nz/en/gulls-terns-and-skuas/page-2|website = teara.govt.nz|access-date = 21 June 2015|publisher = [[Te Ara: The Encyclopedia of New Zealand|Te Ara]]|date = 17 February 2015}}</ref> In breeding season the gull is found on major rivers, especially [[braided river]]s, lakes, and farmland. It generally prefers estuaries and coastal areas outside of the breeding season, though some can be found at breeding sites all year round. The gull is also attracted to urban areas, and "anywhere refuse of scraps available",<ref name= Higgins1996 />{{rp|547}} such as rubbish dumps and [[Slaughterhouse#Freezing works|freezing works]]. In 2019 some gulls established a colony of around 300 birds in [[Christchurch Central City]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Gates |first=Charlie |date=5 November 2019 |title=Urban bird colony in ruins of former office block in Christchurch |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/117183089/urban-bird-colony-in-ruins-of-former-office-block-in-christchurch |work=Stuff.co.nz }}</ref> The species has been sighted occasionally on [[Stewart Island]] and [[Snares Islands / Tini Heke|The Snares]], as well as at altitudes of up to 1700 [[Metres above sea level|MASL]] on the mainland.<ref name= Higgins1996 />{{rp|546–47}} Various colonies also live on the [[North Island]], though it was formerly only a "visitor",<ref name= Higgins1996 />{{rp|547}} the first recorded breeding taking place at [[Lake Rotorua]] in 1932. Some South Island birds cross the [[Cook Strait]] after breeding season to winter in the North Island.<ref name= Higgins1996 /><ref name="IUCN"/>{{rp|548–49}}

