==Status==
In regard to Southland colonies, Rachel McClellan notes that "surveys in the 1970s indicated a population of about 140,000 breeding birds, whereas recent counts gave estimates of only 15–40,000 breeding birds".<ref name = McClellan2009>{{cite thesis |type=PhD |last=McClellan |first=Rachel Katherine |date=2009 |title=The Ecology and Management of Southland's Black-billed Gulls |publisher=University of Otago|url=https://ourarchive.otago.ac.nz/handle/10523/6181}} Nonetheless, different counting methods and the various limitations of these methods mean that "estimates must be treated with caution".</ref>{{rp|13}} This suggests a 6% decline in population every year across thirty years, equivalent to up to 83.6% over the whole period, or 50% if the data are taken conservatively.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|26, 174}} Higher population sizes in the 1950s and 1960s were potentially the result of increased agricultural activity, but the correlation is tenuous.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|13}} Populations at this time were of legendary proportions, with anecdotes telling of farmers who "were forced to wear raincoats so as not to be coated in droppings".<ref name=Morris2019 />{{rp|89}}

Due to "very rapid decline over three generations" the [[IUCN]] has rated the species as [[Near Threatened]].<ref name="IUCN"/> The gull had earlier received a Least Concern rating in 1994, and a Vulnerable rating in 2000.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|13–14}} The [[Department of Conservation (New Zealand)|New Zealand Department of Conservation]] listed the gull as Nationally Critical in 2016.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/Documents/science-and-technical/nztcs19entire.pdf |title=Conservation status of New Zealand birds, 2016 |last=Robertson |first=Hugh A. |display-authors=et al |date=2017 |publisher=New Zealand Department of Conservation }}</ref> It has been referred to in other publications as "critically endangered",<ref name=Morris2019 />{{rp|89}}<ref>{{cite web |url=http://braid.org.nz/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Waimakariri-River-Braided-River-Bird-Breeding-Report-2016-2017-season.pdf |title=Waimakariri River Regional Park Braided River Bird Management 2016–2017 Season |last=Popenhagen |first=Courtney |page=2 |website=BRaid |date=9 January 2024 |publisher=Environment Canterbury: Regional Council}}</ref><ref name = Hudson2017>{{cite news |last=Hudson |first=Daisy |date=3 January 2017 |title=Critically endangered black-billed gull shot with arrow in Timaru |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/timaru-herald/news/88066972/critically-endangered-blackbilled-gull-shot-with-arrow-in-timaru |work=Stuff.co.nz }}</ref> and James Westrip proposed in August 2018 that the gull's status be uplisted to [[Critically Endangered]] in the next BirdLife International Red List report, though it was eventually downlisted in 2020.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://globally-threatened-bird-forums.birdlife.org/2018/08/black-billed-gull-larus-bulleri-revise-global-status/ |title=Black-billed Gull (Larus bulleri): revise global status? |last=Westrip |first=James |date=23 August 2018 |website=BirdLife International: Globally Threatened Bird Forums |access-date=5 January 2019 |archive-date=5 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190105204738/https://globally-threatened-bird-forums.birdlife.org/2018/08/black-billed-gull-larus-bulleri-revise-global-status/ }}</ref> Bill Morris calls the bird "the world's rarest gull".<ref name=Morris2019 />{{rp|90}}

==Threats==
In her study of Southland colonies of black-billed gulls, Rachel McClellan found that eighty per cent of observed chick deaths resulted from predation.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|105}} Introduced mammals, namely ferrets, stoats, cats, and hedgehogs, constitute the "primary factor influencing productivity", that is, nest success, in the colonies.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|147}} Chick predation from the indigenous [[Kelp gull|black-backed gull]] (''Larus dominicanus'') also threatens the black-billed gull population.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|112–13}}

While "the species is relatively tolerant of human disturbance",<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|187}} having potentially benefitted from increasing land conversion for agricultural use since the arrival of Europeans, human activity has also had a negative impact on population size. Largescale shootings of black-billed gulls, such as a 2009 "massacre" of around 200 birds in North Canterbury,<ref>{{cite news |date=18 February 2009 |title=Massacre of native rare birds |url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/217109/Massacre-of-native-rare-birds |work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref> are particularly detrimental to the species' future.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|197}} A similar event was reported in December 2018,<ref>{{cite news |last=Dangerfield|first=Emma|date=19 December 2018 |title=Shooting ends breeding season for endangered gulls on Waimakariri River |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/north-canterbury/109463881/shooting-ends-breeding-season-for-endangered-gulls-on-waimakariri-river |work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref> while another article tells of a gull being discovered with an arrow in it.<ref name = Hudson2017 /> The birds have also been targeted by people in vehicles who "occasionally plough through colonies".<ref name=Morris2019 />{{rp|88}} Morris suggests such actions in part result from confusion with the more common and disliked [[red-billed gull]] (''Chroicocephalus novaehollandiae scopulinus''), which is nonetheless also endangered in New Zealand.<ref name=Morris2019 />{{rp|88, 94–94}} Although no studies have been conducted in this area, previous [[DDT]] usage on farms may affect the breeding success of black-billed gulls and herbicides that remain in use could have consequences that are yet unknown.<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|188}}

McClellan suggests that climate change could have a positive impact on black-billed gull populations, such as in encouraging earlier or extended breeding seasons, but also a negative impact in increasing food availability, which would result in "poor [[reproductive synchrony|synchrony]]".<ref name = McClellan2009 />{{rp|183}} Nesting on river islands, chicks are also vulnerable to flooding. In a January 2018 flood, a single colony lost up to 2500 chicks.<ref>{{cite news |last=Cann|first=Ged|date=15 January 2018 |title=The world's most threatened gull calls New Zealand home, but most Kiwis don't know it |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/environment/99498678/the-worlds-rarest-gull-calls-new-zealand-home-but-most-kiwis-dont-know-it |work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref> Another colony is thought to have lost around 2200 eggs in a flood in November the same year.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dangerfield|first=Emma|date=28 November 2018 |title=Flooding destroys hopes for boost in North Canterbury black-billed gull population |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/news/north-canterbury/108941235/flooding-destroys-hopes-for-boost-in-north-canterbury-blackbilled-gull-population |work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>

In October 2019, Mike Turner responded to a proposal for commercial rafting along the [[Mataura River]], citing concerns for the welfare of black-billed gulls.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rowe|first=Damian|date=13 October 2019 |title=Fish & Game to seek public notification on section of rafting proposal |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/southland-times/116502539/fish--game-to-seek-public-notification-on-section-of-rafting-proposal |work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>

==Conservation efforts==
In October 2018, the Department of Conservation began a trial cull of black-backed gulls along the [[Hurunui River]] to control predation of black-billed gull chicks and other threatened bird species.<ref>{{cite news |date=29 October 2018 |title=Control of black-backed gulls to protect rare braided river birds |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2018/control-of-black-backed-gulls-to-protect-rare-braided-river-birds/ |work=New Zealand Department of Conservation }}</ref> In August 2019, after a successful trial, the department announced a five-year programme extending to the [[Waiau Uwha River]] that aims to reduce the black-backed gull population in the areas by at least eighty per cent.<ref>{{cite news |date=26 August 2019 |title=Rare braided river birds to be protected by gull control |url=https://www.doc.govt.nz/news/media-releases/2019/rare-braided-river-birds-to-be-protected-by-gull-control/ |work=New Zealand Department of Conservation }}</ref>

The black-billed gull placed 30th, with 441 votes, in [[Royal Forest and Bird Protection Society of New Zealand|Forest & Bird's]] 2018 [[Bird of the Year]] competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forestandbird.org.nz/resources/kereru-crowned-bird-year-2018 |title=Kereru crowned Bird of the Year for 2018 |date=15 October 2018 |website=Forest & Bird }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=18 October 2017 |title=Fowl play all aflutter in Bird of the Year competition |url=https://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=11934217 |work=[[The New Zealand Herald]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=20 October 2017 |title=Enough of this nest-feathering politics |url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/opinion/98036999/enough-of-this-nestfeathering-politics |work=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>

